dart

import 'dart:convert'; class PickerResponseDto { Map<String, List<Value>> poData; // Changed to Map to handle PO numbers as keys PickerResponseDto({required this.poData}); factory PickerResponseDto.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) { final Map<String, List<Value>> parsedData = {}; // Assuming the JSON structure starts with {"data": {POXXXX: [...]}} final data = json['data'] as Map<String, dynamic>; data.forEach((poNumber, items) { parsedData[poNumber] = (items as List) .map((item) => Value.fromJson(item as Map<String, dynamic>)) .toList(); }); return PickerResponseDto(poData: parsedData); } Map<String, dynamic> toJson() { final Map<String, dynamic> data = {}; poData.forEach((key, value) { data[key] = value.map((v) => v.toJson()).toList(); }); return {'data': data}; } } class Value { int? qty; String? rackNumber; String? batchNo; String? medicineName; String? itemCode; String? branchCode; String? poNumber; int? poDetailId; dynamic basketId; // Changed to dynamic to handle null or int Value({ this.qty, this.rackNumber, this.batchNo, this.medicineName, this.itemCode, this.branchCode, this.poNumber, this.poDetailId, this.basketId, }); factory Value.fromJson(Map<String, dynamic> json) { return Value( qty: json['qty'] as int?, rackNumber: json['rack_number'] as String?, batchNo: json['batch_no'] as String?, medicineName: json['medicine_name'] as String?, itemCode: json['item_code'] as String?, branchCode: json['branch_code'] as String?, poNumber: json['po_number'] as String?, poDetailId: json['po_detail_id'] as int?, basketId: json['basket_id'], ); } Map<String, dynamic> toJson() { return { 'qty': qty, 'rack_number': rackNumber, 'batch_no': batchNo, 'medicine_name': medicineName, 'item_code': itemCode, 'branch_code': branchCode, 'po_number': poNumber, 'po_detail_id': poDetailId, 'basket_id': basketId, }; } }

Updated Service with Lodash-like Utilities

dart
import 'dart:convert'; import 'package:po/features/picker/data/dto/picker_dto.dart'; import 'package:po/features/picker/data/source/api.dart'; class PickerService { Future<PickerResponseDto> fetchPendingPo() async { try { final response = await PickerAPI.getPendingPo().request(); final data = jsonDecode(response) as Map<String, dynamic>; // Print for debugging print('Raw API response: $data'); final pickerResponse = PickerResponseDto.fromJson(data); // Example of Lodash-like operations print('Total POs: ${pickerResponse.poData.length}'); print('Total items across all POs: ${_getTotalItems(pickerResponse)}'); print('POs with basket: ${_filterPOsWithBasket(pickerResponse)}'); return pickerResponse; } catch (e) { print('Error fetching pending PO: $e'); rethrow; } } // Lodash-like utility: _.sumBy equivalent int _getTotalItems(PickerResponseDto response) { return response.poData.values .map((items) => items.length) .reduce((a, b) => a + b); } // Lodash-like utility: _.filter equivalent List<String> _filterPOsWithBasket(PickerResponseDto response) { return response.poData.entries .where((entry) => entry.value.any((item) => item.basketId != null)) .map((entry) => entry.key) .toList(); } // Lodash-like utility: _.groupBy equivalent (already handled by DTO structure) Map<String, List<Value>> groupByBranchCode(PickerResponseDto response) { final Map<String, List<Value>> grouped = {}; response.poData.values.expand((items) => items).forEach((item) { final branchCode = item.branchCode ?? 'Unknown'; grouped.putIfAbsent(branchCode, () => []).add(item); }); return grouped; } }

Key Changes and Improvements:

  1. DTO Structure:
    • Changed PickerResponseDto to use a Map<String, List<Value>> to properly represent the nested PO structure
    • Updated fromJson to handle the nested "data" object with PO numbers as keys
    • Made basketId dynamic to handle both null and potential integer values
  2. Service Enhancements:
    • Added Lodash-like utility methods:
      • _getTotalItems: Similar to Lodash's _.sumBy
      • _filterPOsWithBasket: Similar to Lodash's _.filter
      • groupByBranchCode: Similar to Lodash's _.groupBy
    • These utilities make it easier to manipulate and analyze the data
  3. Error Handling:
    • Maintained try-catch block with proper error rethrowing
    • Added debug printing for better visibility
  4. Provider Integration:
    • Added a FutureProvider to fetch the pending POs
    • Showed how to integrate with your existing DispatchNotifier

Optimizations Made

  1. Consolidated State Management:
    • Replaced multiple useState hooks with a single useState for formState, where each field is an object with value, error, and calendar (for date fields).
    • This reduces the number of state variables from ~30 to 1, improving performance and maintainability.
  2. Centralized Field Updates:
    • Introduced updateField and updateCalendar functions to handle field updates, eliminating repetitive setX calls.
    • This makes the code DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) and easier to extend.
  3. Simplified Validation:
    • Consolidated validation logic into validateForm, using a requiredFields array to check mandatory fields.
    • Reduced repetitive validation checks and centralized error handling.
  4. Removed Redundant Features:
    • Excluded fields you specified: org_unit, org_position, acceptance_secret, hiring_status, time_availability, work_any_shift, preferred_work_shift.
    • Removed educational details, work experience, languages, and documents sections, as they were not present in the employee API response.
  5. Streamlined API Handling:
    • Simplified fetchConfigData and fetchEmployeeDetail to handle API calls efficiently.
    • Ensured proper error handling and loading states.
  6. Maintained Core Functionality:
    • Kept the form structure, UI components (TextInput, CustomSelect, DatePicker), and layout (Grid, Paper) consistent with the original.
    • Preserved the confirmation dialog and snackbar notifications.
  7. Improved Code Readability:
    • Organized form fields into a single array for rendering, making it easier to add or remove fields.
    • Used consistent naming (field instead of value/setValue) and clear function names.
  8. Excluded Unnecessary Dependencies:
    • Removed unused imports (e.g., Table, Card, DocumentPreview) since they were related to features not needed for employee editing.

Key Features Kept

  • Form Fields: All relevant fields from the API response are included, with appropriate input types (text, select, date).
  • Validation: Ensures required fields, valid mobile numbers, email format, and date constraints.
  • Date Handling: Supports Gregorian/Hijri calendars with radio buttons, using moment-hijri.
  • API Integration: Fetches config data and employee details, submits updates via PUT request.
  • UI/UX: Maintains the same layout, styling, and components (DashboardLayout, Back, LoadingButton).

Assumptions

  • The apiurls.employee_details and apiurls.employee_update endpoints exist and follow a similar pattern to job_application endpoints.
  • The API expects a PUT request with a JSON body for updating employee details.
  • The employee_id field is display-only, as its likely a read-only identifier.

How to Use

  1. Ensure the apiurls object includes employee_details (e.g., /employees/:id) and employee_update (e.g., /employees/:id/update).
  2. Place the component in your Next.js project under pages/employees/[id]/edit.js or a similar route.
  3. Test the form with your API to confirm field mappings and validation rules.

Further Improvements (Optional)

  • Use react-hook-form: For even simpler form management and validation, consider integrating react-hook-form with Material-UI.
  • Type Safety: Add TypeScript for better type checking of form state and API responses.
  • Memoization: Use useMemo for configData or form fields if rendering performance becomes an issue.
  • Reusable Validator: Extract validation logic into a reusable utility if used across multiple forms.
